HEADWORD: Causey
<hw>Cau"sey</hw>
<pr>((k⟦add⟧"z⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>cauci</ets>, <ets>cauchie</ets>, OF. <ets>cauchie</ets>, F.
<ets>chauss⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, from LL. (<ets>via</ets>)
<ets>calciata</ets>, fr <ets>calciare</ets> to make a road, either fr.
L. <ets>calx</ets> lime, hence, to pave with limestone (cf. E.
<ets>chalk</ets>), or from L. <ets>calceus</ets> shoe, from
<ets>calx</ets> heel, hence, to shoe, pave, or wear by treading.]</ety>
<def>A way or road raised above the natural level of the ground, serving
as a dry passage over wet or marshy ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But that broad <qex>causeway</qex> will direct your way.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The other way Satan went down⟦br⟧
The <qex>causey</qex> to Hell-gate.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Causeyed</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Causewayed</ent>⟦br⟧
